final_output_text: To sharpen a crayon without a sharp object, the key is to use the principle of thermal expansion and contraction. When a crayon is dipped into hot water, the outer layer of the crayon absorbs heat and expands. This causes the outer part of the crayon to become softer and more malleable. By holding the crayon in place and then shaping the tip back with your fingers, you can effectively reshape the crayon to create a sharper point.

In contrast, using cold water would not cause the same effect. The crayon would not expand or soften in the way it does when heated, making it difficult to reshape the tip. Therefore, the solution involving hot water is more effective for sharpening the crayon without a sharp object.

